msgid "The Full API"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/concepts/full-api.rst:9 f7b3ec94b89c4e038539c4f096eddbc4
msgid ""
"While you have access to this, you should always use the friendly methods"
" listed on :ref:`client-ref` unless you have a better reason not to, like"
" a method not existing or you wanting more control."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/concepts/full-api.rst:14 f240aad3645f4982b6bf34fb71463a7c
msgid "Contents"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/concepts/full-api.rst:17 84f4f2c44bb249cea8fa678b5e6b3bae
msgid "Introduction"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/concepts/full-api.rst:19 323f5cade26947e59e90e5c39666e038
msgid ""
"The :ref:`grammers-client` doesn't offer a method for every single "
"request the Telegram API supports. However, it's very simple to *call* or"
" *invoke* any request defined in Telegram's API."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/concepts/full-api.rst:23 54b115e014ac4aa2ad33b91b025f0a3a
msgid ""
"This section will teach you how to use what Telethon calls the `TL "
"reference`_. The linked page contains a list and a way to search through "
"*all* types generated from the definition of Telegram's API (in ``.tl`` "
"file format, hence the name). These types include requests and "
"constructors."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/concepts/full-api.rst:30 b4b41fd3866446068cdfa4625d62cd5c
msgid ""
"The reason to keep both https://tl.telethon.dev and this documentation "
"alive is that the former allows instant search results as you type, and a"
" \"Copy import\" button. If you like namespaces, you can also do ``from "
"telethon.tl import types, functions``. Both work."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/concepts/full-api.rst:35 1c85a7ad44d74318bcde45791fb296e4
msgid ""
"Telegram makes these ``.tl`` files public, which other implementations, "
"such as Telethon, can also use to generate code. These files are "
"versioned under what's called \"layers\". ``.tl`` files consist of "
"thousands of definitions, and newer layers often add, change, or remove "
"them. Each definition refers to either a Remote Procedure Call (RPC) "
"function, or a type (which the `TL reference`_ calls \"constructors\", as"
" they construct particular type instances)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/concepts/full-api.rst:43 a087e161c3bc498db310b847b5d412ea
msgid ""
"As such, the `TL reference`_ is a good place to go to learn about all "
"possible requests, types, and what they look like. If you're curious "
"about what's been changed between layers, you can refer to the `TL diff`_"
" site."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/concepts/full-api.rst:49 83d913620183432c9bc204a521a4cde3
msgid "Navigating the TL reference"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/concepts/full-api.rst:52 f9dd5016e5d042c28c811239d7abf73c
msgid "Functions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/concepts/full-api.rst:54 5eb0252e7bb549b687d1524bc0f532d1
msgid ""
"\"Functions\" is the term used for the Remote Procedure Calls (RPC) that "
"can be sent to Telegram to ask it to perform something (e.g. \"send "
"message\"). These requests have an associated return type. These can be "
"invoked (\"called\"):"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/concepts/full-api.rst:66 992ead0bf0004ed1b5200f1ec2b163db
msgid ""
"Whenever you find the type for a function in the `TL reference`_, the "
"page will contain the following information:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/concepts/full-api.rst:69 afaca07f65e9490bb9038b9c06db1990
msgid ""
"What type of account can use the method. This information is regenerated "
"from time to time (by attempting to invoke the function under both "
"account types and finding out where it fails). Some requests can only be "
"used by bot accounts, others by user accounts, and others by both."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/concepts/full-api.rst:73 a15b5c043e294b4ba1d966973ecc1f2b
msgid ""
"The TL definition. This helps you get a feel for the what the function "
"looks like. This is not Python code. It just contains the definition in a"
" concise manner."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/concepts/full-api.rst:76 c89f5d7c4d1f4e06bd81805b94e8c99c
msgid ""
"\"Copy import\" button. Does what it says: it will copy the necessary "
"Python code to import the function to your system's clipboard for easy "
"access."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/concepts/full-api.rst:78 b866deed74ec4ad283729957b5c8fe26
msgid ""
"Returns. The returned type. When you invoke the function, this is what "
"the result will be. It also includes which of the constructors can be "
"returned inline, to save you a click."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/concepts/full-api.rst:81 aabec52b5c3a405086293b784c2d8a7e
msgid ""
"Parameters. The parameters accepted by the function, including their "
"type, whether they expect a list, and whether they're optional."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/concepts/full-api.rst:83 79c79557614244bca4444055ef74a162
msgid ""
"Known RPC errors. A best-effort list of known errors the request may "
"cause. This list is not complete and may be out of date, but should "
"provide an overview of what could go wrong."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/concepts/full-api.rst:86 f30af443bf134060b07ee142dabcdb06
msgid ""
"Example. Autogenerated example, showcasing how you may want to call it. "
"Bear in mind that this is *autogenerated*. It may be spitting out non-"
"sense. The goal of this example is not to show you everything you can do "
"with the request, only to give you a feel for what it looks like to use "
"it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/concepts/full-api.rst:91 efb7e4fea1ea443e8698a3fa7de05677
msgid ""
"It is very important to click through the links and navigate to get the "
"full picture. A specific page will show you what the specific function "
"returns and needs as input parameters. But it may reference other types, "
"so you need to navigate to those to learn what those contain or need."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/concepts/full-api.rst:97 a28820908cf9453fbb20cae26e36410c
msgid "Types"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/concepts/full-api.rst:99 7bc47a8e2af04abdbb4751c8d20c0308
msgid ""
"\"Types\" as understood by TL are not actually generated in Telethon. "
"They would be the \"abstract base class\" of the constructors, but since "
"Python is duck-typed, there is hardly any need to generate mostly "
"unnecessary code. The page for a type contains:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/concepts/full-api.rst:104 caf7c89e3d31429e819bd22adbf20297
msgid ""
"Constructors. Every type will have one or more constructors. These "
"constructors *are* generated and can be immported and used."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/concepts/full-api.rst:106 32e288a7708945b292d0fc1028a9e153
msgid ""
"Requests returning this type. A helpful way to find out \"what requests "
"can return this?\". This is how you may learn what request you need to "
"use to obtain a particular instance of a type."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/concepts/full-api.rst:109 4c5d89d71dec44f39a87a443fad81d13
msgid ""
"Requests accepting this type as input. A helpful way to find out \"what "
"requests can use this type as one of their input parameters?\". This is "
"how you may learn where a type is used."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/concepts/full-api.rst:112 c603348bf7b247a29eb19a022eddc973
msgid ""
"Other types containing this type. A helpful way to find out \"where else "
"does this type appear?\". This is how you can walk back through nested "
"objects."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/concepts/full-api.rst:117 7ddfa40def8e47b5a367574d1fc509e8
msgid "Constructors"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/concepts/full-api.rst:119 09f6c60f8230403bbb487f6b94bcc3aa
msgid ""
"Constructors are used to create instances of a particular type, and are "
"also returned when invoking requests. You will have to create instances "
"yourself when invoking requests that need a particular type as input. The"
" page for a constructor contains:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/concepts/full-api.rst:124 e31a3192bee94f77a0c7090190d01172
msgid ""
"Belongs to. The parent type. This is a link back to the types page for "
"the specific constructor. It also contains the sibling constructors "
"inline, to save you a click."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/concepts/full-api.rst:127 417874c1aa7b4d2fb352e68a037af639
msgid "Members. Both the input parameters *and* fields the constructor contains."
msgstr ""

